Strip the Bazel sandbox path from libcrypto's recorded compiler flags.

OpenSSL records the compiler command line into buildinf.h as
compiler_flags[] (crypto/build.info runs util/mkbuildinf.pl with
"$(CC) $(LIB_CFLAGS) $(CPPFLAGS_Q)"), and crypto/cversion.c compiles it
into libcrypto, surfaced via OpenSSL_version(OPENSSL_CFLAGS).  Under
Bazel/rules_foreign_cc that string contains the absolute sandbox
execroot path -- either the cross toolchain's compiler path (e.g.
.../execroot/_main/external/toolchains_musl+.../bin/aarch64-linux-musl-gcc
in the musl static builds) or the -ffile-prefix-map=<execroot>=. flag
added by set_file_prefix_map.  Either way the build host's directory
layout leaks into libcrypto's .rodata and into every binary that
statically links it (cmk-agent-ctl, mk-sql, ...), tripping the package
build-path validator.

rules_foreign_cc exports the execroot as $EXT_BUILD_ROOT, so strip that
single prefix from the recorded flags, mapping it to "." to mirror the
-ffile-prefix-map=$EXT_BUILD_ROOT=. convention.  The substitution only
fires when $EXT_BUILD_ROOT is set, so a plain (non-Bazel) OpenSSL build
is unaffected.  These flags are purely informational; nothing resolves
them as paths.

--- a/util/mkbuildinf.pl
+++ b/util/mkbuildinf.pl
@@ -11,6 +11,15 @@
 
 my $platform = pop @ARGV;
 my $cflags = join(' ', @ARGV);
+# Checkmk: strip the Bazel sandbox/execroot prefix from the recorded
+# compiler flags so it does not leak into libcrypto's buildinf
+# compiler_flags[] (surfaced via OpenSSL_version(OPENSSL_CFLAGS)).
+# EXT_BUILD_ROOT is exported by rules_foreign_cc; when unset (non-Bazel
+# builds) this is a no-op, mirroring -ffile-prefix-map=$EXT_BUILD_ROOT=.
+if (defined($ENV{EXT_BUILD_ROOT}) && $ENV{EXT_BUILD_ROOT} ne '') {
+    my $ext_build_root = $ENV{EXT_BUILD_ROOT};
+    $cflags =~ s/\Q$ext_build_root\E/./g;
+}
 $cflags =~ s(\\)(\\\\)g;
 $cflags = "compiler: $cflags";
 
